The '''Malaita monarch''' ('''''Symposiachrus malaitae''''') is a species of [[passerine]] bird in the monarch flycatcher family [[Monarchidae]].  It is endemic to the island of [[Malaita]] in the [[Solomon Islands (archipelago)|Solomon Islands archipelago]]. It was formerly treated as [[conspecific]] with the [[Solomons monarch]] (''Symposiachrus barbatus'').

==Taxonomy==
The Malaita monarch was [[species description|formally described]] in 1931 by the American ornithologist [[Ernst Mayr]] based on specimens collected on the island of [[Malaita]] in the [[Solomon Islands (archipelago)|Solomon Islands archipelago]]. He considered the specimens to be from a [[subspecies]] of the [[Solomons Monarch]] and coined the [[trinomial name]] ''Monarcha barbata malaitae''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Mayr | first=Ernst | author-link=Ernst Mayr | year=1931 | title=Birds collected during the Whitney South Sea Expedition. 17, The birds of Malaita Island (British Solomon Islands) | journal=American Museum Novitates | issue=504 | page=23 | hdl=2246/4238 | url=http://hdl.handle.net/2246/4238 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=512 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484213 }}</ref> The Malaita monarch is now placed in the genus ''[[Symposiachrus]]'' and is treated as a separate species from the Solomons monarch based on the differences in plumage and genetics.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela C. Rasmussen | date=August 2024 | title=Monarchs | work=IOC World Bird List Version 14.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/monarchs/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=19 September 2024 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Andersen | first1=M.J. | last2=Hosner | first2=P.A. | last3=Filardi | first3=C.E. | last4=Moyle | first4=R.G. | date=2015 | title=Phylogeny of the monarch flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly and novel relationships within a major Australo-Pacific radiation | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=83 | pages=118–136 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2014.11.010| pmid=25463752 | bibcode=2015MolPE..83..118A }}</ref>

